+## Test Coverage Summary
+
+| Test File | Test Class | Test Count | Priority | Tier |
+| --------- | ---------- | ---------- | -------- | ---- |
+| `test_windows_guest_agent_os_info.py` | `TestWindowsGuestAgentOSInfo` | 3 | P0 | Tier 1 |
+| `test_windows_guest_agent_os_info.py` | `TestWindowsGuestAgentInfoAfterReboot` | 1 | P1 | Tier 1 |
+| `test_windows_guest_agent_os_info.py` | `TestWindowsGuestAgentServiceDetection` | 2 | P1 | Tier 3 |
+| **Total** | | **6** | | |
+
+### STP Scenario Mapping
+
+| STP Scenario | Test Method | Priority |
+| ------------ | ----------- | -------- |
+| Scenario 1: Windows OS Info Display | `test_vmi_os_info_matches_windows_os`, `test_vmi_os_info_not_empty` | P0 |
+| Scenario 2: Windows Hostname Display | `test_vmi_hostname_matches_windows_hostname` | P0 |
+| Scenario 3: Info After Reboot | `test_guest_agent_info_available_after_reboot` | P1 |
+| Scenario 4: Agent Start Detection | `test_os_info_appears_when_agent_starts`, `test_os_info_absent_when_agent_stopped` | P1 |
+| Scenario 5: Multiple Windows Versions | Covered via parametrization of VM fixture across Windows versions (implementation detail) | P2 |
+
+---
+
+## Design Decisions
+
+1. **Three separate test classes**: Each class has distinct preconditions and resource lifecycle requirements. Separating them avoids the GRAVEYARD lesson about class-scoped fixtures from different VMs causing scheduling failures.
+
+2. **`TestWindowsGuestAgentOSInfo`** groups the P0 info-display tests that share the same running VM precondition with no state mutation between tests.
+
+3. **`TestWindowsGuestAgentInfoAfterReboot`** is separate because the reboot operation mutates VM state. The precondition explicitly states the VM's info has been verified before the reboot.
+
+4. **`TestWindowsGuestAgentServiceDetection`** is marked tier3 because it involves guest-internal service manipulation (stopping/starting qemu-ga), which is more complex and time-consuming. The two tests in this class have an implicit ordering (stop then start), but are designed to be independent via fixture setup.
+
+5. **Scenario 5 (Multiple Windows Versions)** is handled via parametrization of the VM fixture rather than separate test methods, following the matrix testing pattern used in `tests/virt/cluster/common_templates/windows/`.
+
+6. **No `conftest.py` in STD**: Fixtures are implementation details and will be designed during the code generation phase based on existing utilities (`validate_os_info_vmi_vs_windows_os`, `get_guest_os_info`, `validate_virtctl_guest_agent_after_guest_reboot`).
+
